  "title": "Affect-Logics",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "74403de00cb01401",
      "text": "Thinking vs. Feeling"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "4bcba20643c64bf8",
      "text": "A large part of psychological research revolves around the question of the relationship between thinking and feeling. Does thinking determine feeling or does feeling determine thinking?"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "463d500c97277231",
      "text": "The basis of such questions is the separation between the two. Their background is not difficult to explain. We describe ourselves differently when we are excited, angry, sad or in love than when we are solving arithmetic problems, pondering a crossword puzzle or trying to solve a theoretical problem. But it's not just the way we describe ourselves that is different, so is the way others describe us. We see differences in other people's behavior when they are – as we think – angry or sad. And we get feedback on the fact that people can see what our emotional state is like. There is a close connection between our emotions and our behavior. This applies not only to facial expressions and gestures, but also to more elaborate forms of behavior. When we are afraid, we freeze or flee in panic. If we suddenly feel physically threatened, we flinch, sometimes we strike out reflexively and so on. To summarize, the path from feeling to acting is a short one. Feelings are closely linked to behavioral patterns that enable us to act quickly."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "8d85fb6ed3d8cf66",
      "text": "This is probably the evolutionary advantage associated with the ability (or need) to feel. It leads extremely quickly to behavior-determining decisions. In emergency situations, it enables prompt action without any delay. It can have this effect because it is very closely linked to physical reactions. For example, in situations that are experienced as dangerous, emergency mechanisms are activated on a physical, physiological level, releasing the strength needed for a fight. Processes that are not necessary for immediate survival are reduced, while those that are essential for fight or flight are increased."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "861e0db635e44f68",
      "text": "The price for the schematization and speed of affective reactions and the risk lies in the very thing that constitutes their advantage: the elimination of reflection, analysis and sober, rational thinking."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "46798790965699bc",
      "text": "These are mental activities that require time. The observer's perspective that is adopted during thinking is the external perspective. The object of the investigation is viewed from a distance, you have time to engage with other real or fictitious observers and take their points of view into account, weigh up different descriptions, explanations and evaluations, and so on. You can also question yourself or at least the principles of your own observations. This type of thinking constructs - more or less laboriously - generating mechanisms (explanations) for the observed phenomena."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "e0484b24814b7832",
      "text": "The difference between thinking and feeling can most simply be characterized as a difference between the internal and external perspective of observation. Feelings provide an immediately effective instruction for action for the actor involved in the interaction or, to put it another way: they increase the probability that this instruction is not consciously perceived as an instruction at all, but is implemented immediately - here and now. Thinking, on the other hand, provides the perspective of the spectator who observes the actor or the entire interaction. In doing so, it can \"leave\" the present and construct the past and future imaginatively and fictitiously. To a certain extent, it can carry out historical analyses (\"How could it happen that ...?\") and forecast and plan the future (\"How can it be achieved that ...?\"). It is able to be \"objective\", i.e. to abstract from the subjective conditions of the observer (which does not mean that this always or even often succeeds or is desirable or leads to meaningful results)."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "0480a7ea46cafeb5",
      "text": "In view of these different ways of functioning, it makes sense to consider thinking and feeling as separate. All the more so as both are apparently also physiologically linked to the function of different areas of the brain. However, this separation does not seem appropriate, as thinking and feeling are also closely linked functionally. The way we think influences the way we feel, and the way we feel influences the way we think. The Swiss psychiatrist Luc Ciompi has coined the neat term \"affect logic\" to describe this very succinctly. He sees feeling and thinking as an integrated system in which, depending on the context, other affect logic schemes are activated. When someone loves, they use a different coordination of affects and logical (or illogical) thinking than when they hate."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "0682610ed49ed0db",
      "text": "This coordination of thinking and feeling seems to take on a special form in times of war. We will take a brief look at it in the following sections.\n"
    },
