        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "e0484b24814b7832",
        "text": "The difference between thinking and feeling can most simply be characterized as a difference between the internal and external perspective of observation. Feelings provide an immediately effective instruction for action for the actor involved in the interaction or, to put it another way: they increase the probability that this instruction is not consciously perceived as an instruction at all, but is implemented immediately - here and now. Thinking, on the other hand, provides the perspective of the spectator who observes the actor or the entire interaction. In doing so, it can \"leave\" the present and construct the past and future imaginatively and fictitiously. To a certain extent, it can carry out historical analyses (\"How could it happen that ...?\") and forecast and plan the future (\"How can it be achieved that ...?\"). It is able to be \"objective\", i.e. to abstract from the subjective conditions of the observer (which does not mean that this always or even often succeeds or is desirable or leads to meaningful results)."
      },
      "date": 1710420601610
