      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "0480a7ea46cafeb5",
        "text": "In view of these different ways of functioning, it makes sense to consider thinking and feeling as separate. All the more so as both are apparently also physiologically linked to the function of different areas of the brain. However, this separation does not seem appropriate, as thinking and feeling are also closely linked functionally. The way we think influences the way we feel, and the way we feel influences the way we think. The Swiss psychiatrist Luc Ciompi has coined the neat term \"affect logic \"59 to describe this very succinctly. He sees feeling and thinking as an integrated system in which, depending on the context, other affect logic schemes are activated. When someone loves, they use a different coordination of affects and logical (or illogical) thinking than when they hate."
